25. Acherusia templa, ‘the realm of Acheron,’ i.e. hell, the place where the wicked suffer after death. Popular superstition repre· sented this as beneath the earth; but Lucr., who with the mind's eye can penetrate through the earth, sees that there is no hell there.

templa is used freely in old Latin in the sense of loca: Lucr. has linguai templa (iv 624) ‘the mouth,' mentis templa (v 103); Plautus speaks of the sea as Neptunia templa (Mil. Glor. 413).
